(1973, 1, '2015-01-28 05:52:33', '2015-01-28 05:52:33', 'One of my favorite treats, the popsicle. Truth be told, I am not much of an ice cream gal- but I may help myself to a popsicle or two any warm nite. Although summer is winding down, the heat is still up in the 80''s + I figured I would share how to make one of my favorite homemade treats...<!--more-->\r\n\r\nI love eating natural foods. Even better when they taste like real treats! Also a huge citrus fan. I was the weird one growing up that always wanted orange flavored anything {to this day I still do not get why it''s the last one to get picked? Meant I always had my way I suppose!}. + At the gelato place, lemon is always an option- so many perks! + Then the mix with fresh herbs- delightful, right? Cucumber to add a little balance to the acidity + you''re off....\r\n\r\nThese measurements are approximate. Here''s what you need:\r\n\r\nsix organic small-medium lemons\r\n\r\none organic small cucumber\r\n\r\none bunch of fresh mint\r\n\r\nthree tablespoons of agave\r\n\r\nthree cups of water\r\n\r\npopsicle mold {there are so many cute options on Amazon!}\r\n\r\n<a href="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/homemadelemonpopsicle.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-980" alt="homemadelemonpopsicle" src="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/homemadelemonpopsicle.jpg" width="3264" height="2176" /></a>Firstly I cut off the lemon rinds, you don''t have to make it perfect because a little rind in the popsicle is nice. Then using a juicer, I have my Breville, juice together lemons + cucumber. Set aside.<a href="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/homemadepopsicle.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-981" alt="homemadepopsicle" src="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/homemadepopsicle.jpg" width="3264" height="2176" /></a> Bring three cups of water to a boil + then add mint leaves {saving two sprigs of fresh mint out} + agave, simmer for 6 minutes. You have taken all the goodness + flavor from the mint, strain them + add the mint agave liquid to the lemon + cucumber juice.<a href="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/lemonpopsicle.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-984" alt="lemonpopsicle" src="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/lemonpopsicle.jpg" width="3264" height="2176" /></a>\r\n\r\nLet cool. This is when you taste test! Is the sweetness, tartness to your liking? You can add a little more water or squeeze fresh lemon juice or add more agave if adjustments are needed. Just note that when it freezes, the flavor is dulled a touch, so you want it to be a little stronger than what you''d like. Then, using my pyrex for easy no-spill pours, fill up your popsicle molds. How pretty is the color?<a href="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/lemonmintpopsicle.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-983" alt="lemonmintpopsicle" src="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/lemonmintpopsicle.jpg" width="3264" height="2176" /></a>\r\n\r\nFinally you''ll add one fresh mint leaf to each mold, this makes them oh so pretty! Then I set the sticks in it + freeze for 8 hours. <a href="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/lemoncucumberpopsicle.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-982" alt="lemoncucumberpopsicle" src="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/lemoncucumberpopsicle.jpg" width="3264" height="2176" /></a><a href="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/photo-2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-990" alt="photo 2" src="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/photo-2.jpg" width="2959" height="1973" /></a>\r\n\r\nVoila! A delicious treat, quick, easy + good for you too... X', 'Cool It/ lemon cucumber mint popsicles', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '979-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-01-28 05:52:33', '2015-01-28 05:52:33', '', 979, 'http://182.71.22.42/sarah/?p=1973', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
