(1980, 1, '2015-01-28 05:55:44', '2015-01-28 05:55:44', 'So it''s summer + we are all about spending long days in the pool, surviving the heat. Well, what happens when your beauty blonde locks get attacked by some killer chlorine? I used one of my nearest + dearest, Brittany, to show you how you can recoop the babe hair...<!--more-->\r\n\r\nShe was sweet enough to let me use her tragedy for my heroic beauty fix! Here is the damage... When blonde hair is super processed, <em>the hair becomes porous + absorbs anything + everything</em> very quickly. The ends of her hair were a pretty shade of mint green. Yes, if you''re into it, those crazy pastels are trending at the moment. But if not, it''s time to get to work.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/greenhair.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-914" alt="greenhair" src="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/greenhair.jpg" width="464" height="464" /></a><a href="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/bakingsodafix2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-913" alt="bakingsodafix2" src="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/bakingsodafix2.jpg" width="480" height="480" /></a>\r\n\r\nStart by creating a <em>baking soda paste</em>. The amount you need depends on how much of your hair needs a little strip. For Brittany''s ends, 4 Tablespoons to 1 cup of water. You may need to add a little more of either to get a paste like consistency. Mix it + then generously apply to the damaged portion of the hair.Â  Leave on for 15 minutes. This process IS tough on your hair. You are stripping the green out, so don''t try + be a champ + keep it on for a long time, it will kill your hair.\r\n\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-911" alt="bakingsodaconditionfix" src="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/bakingsodaconditionfix.jpg" width="2279" height="2279" />\r\n\r\nNext, rinse baking soda thoroughly +<em> do a quick purple shampoo</em>, I love Magic Lights {which IS tricky to find in the USA hence why I stock up every time I am in Canada}. I say quick because again, your hair is already vulnerable + porous, but the purple will tone your color. Rinse with cold water. Then you need to rebuild your hair! I love the <a href="http://www.ojon.com/product/4735/15439/index.tmpl" target="_blank">Ojon Restorative Treatment</a>; warm the product in your fingers so it becomes emollient then apply to your damp hair, all over. Wrap your head with saran wrap + leave for 30 mins. Then rinse. If you find your hair is still a little fragile, follow up with Ojon again 3/4 days later.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/greenhairBT.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-910" alt="greenhairBT" src="http://sarahappleby.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/greenhairBT.jpg" width="3264" height="2176" /></a>Here''s the babe hair rebuilt! HMU by me. + Next time you are dipping into a pool, consider using a hair protectant or sealant to keep the blonde hair bombshell! Here''s to happy blonde locks, hey <a href="http://okbrittanyt.tumblr.com/" target="_blank">Brittany</a>!... X\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'When great hair goes green.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '909-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-01-28 05:55:44', '2015-01-28 05:55:44', '', 909, 'http://182.71.22.42/sarah/?p=1980', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
